tp://www.irishtimes.com/news/crime-and-law/courts/three-men-sentenced-for-sexual-abuse-of-teenage-girl-1.1984164|accessdate=6 August 2015|work=Irish Times|date=31 October 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141102004824/http://www.irishtimes.com/news/crime-and-law/courts/three-men-sentenced-for-sexual-abuse-of-teenage-girl-1.1984164|archivedate=2 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Three Kildare men sentenced for sex abuse of teenage girl |url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/ireland/three-kildare-men-sentenced-for-sex-abuse-of-teenage-girl-649354.html |accessdate=6 August 2015 |work=Irish Examiner |date=31 October 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141102173453/http://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/ireland/three-kildare-men-sentenced-for-sex-abuse-of-teenage-girl-649354.html |archivedate=2 November 2014 |url-status=unfit }}</ref>\n\n==Personal Life==\nHe is the cousin of [[Fuad Sule]], who is also a professional footballer.<ref>https://www.the42.ie/fuad-sule-bohemians-interview-3408290-May2017/</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Akinade was absent for half the season due to an illness, in February 2017 he had his spleen removed and returned in June 2018.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bohemians boss Keith Long admits his side are missing Ismahil Akinade|url=http://www.irishmirror.ie/sport/soccer/soccer-news/bohemians-boss-keith-long-admits-10420566}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2017, Akinade was issued a [[deportation]] order. His application to have the deportation stopped was rejected in the [[High Court (Ireland)|High Court]] in May 2019.<ref name=\"ishmaildeportation\">{{cite web |title=Z.A. -v- The Minister for Justice and Equality |url=http://www.courts.ie/Judgments.nsf/768d83be24938e1180256ef30048ca51/742f5c6a7cadd0dd80258412004e5c63?OpenDocument |website=courts.ie |accessdate=27 June 2019}}</ref> He returned to Nigeria voluntarily in June.<ref name=\"akinadeexit\">{{cite news |last1=Ward |first1=Johnny |title=Blow for Waterford as Akinade makes swift exit |url=https://www.rte.ie/sport/soccer/2019/0624/1057321-blow-for-waterford-as-akinade-makes-swift-exit/ |accessdate=27 June 2019 |work=RT\u00c9 News |date=25 June 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"independentfaildeportation\">{{cite news |last1=Brady |first1=Tom |title=Soccer star deported from Ireland joins Vietnamese outfit on lucrative deal |url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/courts/soccer-star-deported-from-ireland-joins-vietnamese-outfit-on-lucrative-deal-38261275.html |accessdate=28 June 2019 |work=Irish Independent |date=28 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n===Club===\n'''Bohemians'''\n*[[Leinster Senior Cup (association football)|Lenister Senior Cup]]: [[2015\u201316 Leinster Senior Cup|2015\u201316]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Soccerway|252497}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Akinade, Ismahil}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1994 births]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Ibadan]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Nigerian footballers]]\n[[Category:League of Ireland players]]\n[[Category:Bray Wanderers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:St Patrick's Athletic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bohemian F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Waterford F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Nigerian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Nigerian expatriate sportspeople in Ireland]]\n[[Category:Expatriate association footballers in the Republic of Ireland]]\n[[Category:Leinster Senior League (association football) players]]\n", "name_user": "2001:bb6:7739:6d00:346b:bfe0:63cd:1dc3", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ismahil_Akinade"}
{"title_page": "Grim Sleeper", "text_new": "{{short description|American serial killer (1952\u20132020)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox murderer\n|birth_name= Lonnie David Franklin Jr.\n|image= Lonnie David Franklin (Grim Sleeper).png\n|caption= LAPD mug shot 1998\n|birth_date= {{birth date|1952|08|30}}\n|birth_place= [[Los Angeles, California]], U.S.\n|death_date={{death date and age|2020|03|28|1952|08|30}}\n|death_place= [[San Quentin State Prison]]\n|alias= Grim Sleeper<br>Southside Slayer<br>25 Auto Killer<br>\n|sentence= [[Capital punishment in the United States|Death]]\n|victims= 10-25+ victims, 1 survivor (known)\n|country= United States\n|states= California\n|beginyear= 1985\n|endyear= 2007 (known murders)\n|apprehended= July 7, 2010\n|children= 2\n}}\n\n'''Lonnie David Franklin, Jr.''' (August 30, 1952 &ndash; March 28, 2020),<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2020-03-29/grim-sleeper-serial-killer-lonnie-franklin-dies-death-row-san-quentin|title='Grim Sleeper' serial killer Lonnie Franklin dies on death row at San Quentin|date=March 29, 2020|website=Los Angeles Times}}</ref> better known by the nickname '''Grim Sleeper''', was an American [[serial killer]] who was responsible for at least ten murders and one attempted murder in [[Los Angeles]], California.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/crime/grim-sleeper-serial-killer-lonnie-franklin-dead/|title='Grim Sleeper' Serial Killer Lonnie Franklin Dies in California Prison Cell|website=PEOPLE.com}}</ref> He was also convicted for [[rape]] and [[sexual violence]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/grim-sleeper-guilty-killings_us_572bb5e3e4b016f37895382f|title=Man Found Guilty For All 10 'Grim Sleeper' Killings Of Women|date=2016-05-05|website=The Huffington Post|access-date=2016-05-05}}</ref><ref name=LAWeekly0>Christine Pelisek, [http://www.laweekly.com/2008-08-28/news/grim-sleeper/. Grim Sleeper Returns: He's Murdering Angelenos, as Cops Hunt his DNA], ''LA Weekly'', August 28, 2008</ref><ref name=sky>[http://news.sky.com/story/631629/grim-sleeper-serial-killer-hunted Grim Sleeper Serial Killer Hunted ] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160610190831/http://news.sky.com/story/631629/grim-sleeper-serial-killer-hunted |date=2016-06-10 }}, SkyNews Report</ref> Franklin earned his nickname when he appeared to have taken a 14-year break from his crimes, from 1988 to 2002.<ref name=msn>{{cite web |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/38133825 |title=Arrest in 'Grim Sleeper' killings of ten women, man |publisher=NBC News |accessdate=2010-07-08}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2010, Franklin was arrested as a suspect, and, after many delays, his trial began in February 2016. On May 5, 2016, the jury convicted him of killing nine women and one teenage girl.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/05/05/us/grim-sleeper-trial-verdict/index.html|title=Jury convicts 'Grim Sleeper' of 10 murders|author=Scott Glover and Paul Vercammen|website=CNN|access-date=2016-05-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/trial-begins-alleged-grim-sleeper-serial-killer-lonnie/story?id=36974945|title=Trial Begins for Accused 'Grim Sleeper' Serial Killer|date=2016-02-17|publisher=ABC News|access-date=2016-05-05}}</ref> On June 6, 2016, the jury recommended the [[death penalty]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-grim-sleeper-death-verdict-20160606-snap-story.html|title=Jurors vote for death sentence for 'Grim Sleeper' serial killer|last=Times|first=Los Angeles|website=latimes.com|access-date=2016-06-06}}</ref> and on August 10, 2016, the Los Angeles Superior Court sentenced him to death for each of the ten victims named in the verdict.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-grim-sleeper-sentencing-20160810-snap-story.html|title=The 'Grim Sleeper' is sentenced to death for string of murders|last=Gerber|first=Marisa|last2=Queally|first2=James|date=10 August 2016|website=latimes.com|publisher=Los Angeles Times|access-date=2016-08-10}}</ref>  On March 28, 2020, he was found unresponsive in his cell at [[San Quentin State Prison]] and pronounced dead.\n\n==Personal life==\nLonnie Franklin Jr. was born on August 30, 1952. He grew up in [[South Central Los Angeles]], California.{{cn|date=December 2019}} He married and had two children.{{cn|date=December 2019}} He was given a [[general discharge]] from the [[United States Army]] on July 24, 1975, after having been released from prison for his conviction of gang-raping a 17-year-old girl in [[Stuttgart]], [[West Germany]].<ref name=\"people.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/crime/grim-sleeper-serial-killer-lonnie-franklin-once-gang-raped-a-german-teen/|title='Grim Sleeper' Serial Killer Lonnie Franklin Once Gang Raped a German Teen|website=PEOPLE.com}}</ref>\n\nFranklin and two other servicemen stationed in Stuttgart stopped to ask directions from the teen then offered her a ride home. When she accepted, they put a knife to her throat, drove her to a field and repeatedly raped her. She was able to feign interest in Franklin and asked for his phone number, by which police identified him.<ref name=\"people.com\"/>\n\nDuring the [[gang rape]] photographs were taken by one of the rapists \u2013 as was the case with the women Lonnie Franklin raped and murdered.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abc7.com/1356478/|title=Grim Sleeper jury to hear testimony from earliest known victim|date=May 26, 2016|website=ABC7 Los Angeles}}</ref>\n\nIn 1989, he was also convicted of two charges of theft, one charge of misdemeanor assault, and one charge of [[Battery (crime)|battery]]. He served time for one of the theft charges.<ref name=abcnews1>{{cite news |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Nightline/familys-dna-led-police-grim-sleeper-serial-killer/story?id=11116381&page=2|title=New Technique of Using Family's DNA Led Police to 'Grim Sleeper' Suspect|publisher=ABC News|date=2010-07-08|accessdate=2010-07-23}}</ref>\n\n==Investigation==\nIn the 1980s, the [[Los Angeles Police Department|LAPD]] marked the deaths of several women in [[South Los Angeles, California|South Los Angeles]] with the identification \u201cNHI\u201d, meaning \"no humans involved\",{{citation needed|date=November 2019}} which was used for cases involving chronic [[drug user]]s and [[prostitution in the United States|prostitutes]]. Margaret Prescod formed the \"Black Women Count\" movement with community members to pressure the LAPD into acknowledging the deaths as serial killings and forming a task force in response. The coalition launched a media campaign and set a monetary reward aiming to capture the killer. The joint LAPD-[[Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department]] investigation determined that the crimes were committed by a single person labeled the \"Southside Slayer\". Their results were announced to the public on September 23, 1985.<ref name=SSS/>\n\nAccording to investigators, evidence was found suggesting that several serial killers were murdering women in South Los Angeles. [[Louis Craine]] committed at least two of the \"Southside Slayer\" murders, and [[Michael Hughes (serial killer)|Michael Hughes]], [[Daniel Lee Siebert]], [[Chester Turner]], and [[Ivan Hill]] committed at least one each.<ref>{{cite web |title= Map: Serial Killers in South L.A. |work= Los Angeles Times |date= 3 August 2010 |url= http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-serialkillersmap-0804-i,0,515310.htmlstory |accessdate= }}</ref> A separate series of killings commenced with the murder of Debra Jackson and a different ''[[modus operandi]]'' involving a firearm.<ref name=SSS>{{cite web |last= Jones |first= Jack |title= Man Sought in Slayings of 10 L.A.-Area Prostitutes |work= Los Angeles Times |publisher= |date= 24 September 1985 |url= http://articles.latimes.com/1985-09-24/news/mn-18536_1 |accessdate= }}</ref> These became known, misleadingly, as the \"Strawberry Murders.\" Sheriff's Detective Rickey Ross was wrongfully arrested due to a ballistics error. Two decades later, the perpetrator of these crimes was dubbed the \"Grim Sleeper\" due to the long period of apparent inactivity between murders.<ref>{{cite web |author=Jill Stewart |url=http://www.laweekly.com/2010-07-15/news/missing-the-grim-sleeper-by-a-hair/1 |title=Missing the Grim Sleeper by a Hair|work=LA Weekly |date=2010-07-15 |accessdate=2010-12-18}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2007, the slaying of Janecia Peters, 25, was linked through [[DNA]] analysis to at least eleven unsolved murders in Los Angeles, the first of which occurred in 1985. That same year, in secrecy, the LAPD formed the \"800 Task Force,\" composed of six detectives and overseen by the Robbery-Homicide Unit. After a four-month investigation, ''[[LA Weekly]]'' [[investigative journalism|investigative reporter]] Christine Pelisek broke the news of the task force's existence, the link between Peters' killing and the earlier murders, and the silence of [[Mayor of Los Angeles|Mayor]] [[Antonio Villaraigosa]] and Police Chief [[William J. Bratton]] regarding the killer's existence. Villaraigosa and Bratton neither issued a press release nor warned the community. In some cases, ''LA Weekly'' was the first to inform the families that their daughters had long been confirmed as victims of a serial killer.<ref name=LAWeekly0/>\n\nIn early September 2008, Los Angeles officials announced that they were offering a $500,000 reward to help catch the killer.<ref name=sky/> On November 1, the case was featured on the [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] program ''[[America's Most Wanted]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.amw.com/fugitives/brief.cfm?id=60381/ |title=Most Wanted fugitives website (defunct) |date= |work=[[America's Most Wanted]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022040939/http://www.amw.com/ |archivedate=2012-10-22 |accessdate=2015-02-20}}{{full citation needed|date=July 2010}}</ref> On February 25, 2009, Bratton addressed the press for the first time regarding the case, at which time the police formally gave the killer the \"Grim Sleeper\" nickname chosen by ''LA Weekly''. Bratton also released a [[9-1-1]] call from the 1980s in which a man reported seeing a body being dumped by Franklin, giving a detailed description and license plate number of a van connected with the now-closed Cosmopolitan Church.<ref>{{cite web |last=Pelisek |first=Christine |url=http://blogs.laweekly.com/ladaily/1tape-may-hold-clue-to-identif/ |title=Tape May Hold Clue to Identifying Grim Sleeper Serial Killer \u2013 Los Angeles News \u2013 The Informer |publisher=Blogs.laweekly.com |date=2009-02-25 |accessdate=2010-07-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090803080447/http://blogs.laweekly.com/ladaily/1tape-may-hold-clue-to-identif/ |archive-date=2009-08-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2009, Pelisek conducted an extensive interview with Enietra Washington, the sole survivor of Franklin's attacks.<ref>{{cite web |author=Christine Pelisek |url=http://www.laweekly.com/2008-08-28/news/grim-sleeper/4 |title=Grim Sleeper Returns: He's Murdering Angelenos, as Cops Hunt his DNA|work=LA Weekly |date=2008-08-28 |accessdate=2010-07-08}}</ref><ref name=LAWeekly1>{{cite web |author=Christine Pelisek |url=http://www.laweekly.com/2009-03-12/news/grim-sleeper-39-s-sole-survivor/2 |title=Grim Sleeper's Sole Survivor|work=LA Weekly |date=2009-03-12 |accessdate=2010-07-08}}</ref> Washington described him as \"a black man in his early 30s [\u2060\u200a\u2060.\u2060\u200a\u2060.\u2060\u200a\u2060.\u2060\u200a\u2060] He looked neat. Tidy. Kind of geeky. He wore a black polo shirt tucked into khaki trousers.\" She also described the interior and exterior of his vehicle.<ref name=survive>{{cite web |author=Christine Pelisek |url=http://www.laweekly.com/2009-03-12/news/grim-sleeper-39-s-sole-survivor/ |title=Grim Sleeper's Sole Survivor|work=LA Weekly |date=2009-03-12 |accessdate=2010-07-08}}</ref>\n\n==Arrest==\nOn July 7, 2010, the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' reported that an arrest had been made. Los Angeles County District Attorney Steve Cooley identified the suspect as 57-year-old Lonnie David Franklin Jr., a mechanic who worked between 1981 and 1988 for the City of Los Angeles in the sanitation department and briefly for the LAPD.<ref name=msn/> Franklin was identified for arrest, at least in part, on [[DNA profiling#DNA evidence as evidence in criminal trials|familial DNA analysis]].<ref name=latimesblog>{{cite news |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2010/07/lapd-make-arrest-in-grim-sleeper-serial-killings.html |title=LAPD make arrest in Grim Sleeper serial killings |publisher=Latimesblogs.latimes.com |date= 2010-07-07|accessdate=2010-07-08}}</ref>\n\nPolice had found no exact match between DNA found at the crime scenes and any of the profiles in California's DNA profile database, so they searched the database for stored profiles that demonstrated sufficient similarity to allow police to infer a familial relationship. They found similar DNA belonging to Franklin's son, Christopher, who had been convicted of a [[felony]] weapons charge. According to Cooley, detectives then used a piece of discarded pizza with Franklin's DNA to make the link.<ref name=yahoonews1/>\n\nOne undercover police officer pretended to be a waiter at a restaurant where Franklin ate, collecting dishes, silverware, glasses, and pizza crusts to obtain DNA.<ref name=yahoonews1/> The identification was used to arrest Franklin after his DNA was obtained and deemed a match.<ref name=CNN1/> Saliva found on the victims established a DNA match linking Franklin to the deaths.<ref name=abcnews1/>\n\nLaw enforcement missed an opportunity to catch Franklin because his DNA was not previously collected. In 2003, Franklin was convicted of a felony and was serving three years of supervised [[probation]]. In 2004, voters passed [[California Proposition 69 (2004)|Proposition 69]], which requires that DNA must be collected from all felons and everyone arrested on some specified charges. It also requires the expansion of the DNA database. Authorities collected and sorted through thousands of DNA samples. While he was on probation, Franklin's DNA was supposed to be entered in the system but was not as probation officers did not collect samples from people who were on unsupervised probation between November 2004 and August 2005. The probation department did not have the resources to collect samples until August 2005.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/jul/15/local/la-me-grim-sleeper-dna-20100715|title=Authorities Missed A Chance to Catch Grim Sleeper Suspect|work=Los Angeles Times|date=2010-07-15|accessdate=2010-07-23|first=Jack|last=Leonard}}</ref>\n\nOn December 16, 2010, the LAPD released 180 photos of women, found in Franklin's home after unsuccessful attempts to identify the individuals, possibly additional victims. \"These people are not suspects, we don't even know if they are victims, but we do know this: Lonnie Franklin's reign of terror in the city of Los Angeles, which spanned well over two decades, culminating with almost a dozen murder victims, certainly needs to be investigated further,\" said Police Chief [[Charlie Beck]].<ref name=reuters1/>\n\nIn all, investigators found over 1,000 photos and several hundred hours of video in his home.<ref name=reuters1>{{cite news |last=Whitcomb |first=Dan |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSTRE6BF6EU20101216 |title=L.A. police release photos of possible Grim Sleeper victims |publisher=Reuters |date= 2010-12-16|accessdate=2010-12-18}}</ref> The images show mainly black women of a wide age range, from teenagers to middle-aged and older, often nude. Police believe Franklin took many of the pictures, which show both conscious and unconscious individuals, dating back 30 years.<ref name=reuters1/> The photos were released to the public in an effort to identify the women.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hayes |first=Kevin |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-504083_162-20026038-504083.html |title=\"Grim Sleeper\" Photos: LAPD Deluged with Calls - Crimesider |publisher=CBS News |accessdate=2010-12-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://abcnews.go.com/TheLaw/grim-sleeper-serial-killer-victim-photos-released-los/story?id=12424559 |title=Five Women Tentatively Identified in 'Grim Sleeper' Cas - ABC News |publisher=Abcnews.go.com |accessdate=2010-12-18}}</ref>\n\nOn November 3, 2011, [[Reuters]] reported that the police were considering Franklin as a suspect in six more slayings of additional female victims. The police were investigating two of the six as potential victims killed during a 14-year lapse between an initial spate of Grim Sleeper murders that ended in 1988 and several more that began in 2002. Of the remaining four victims, two bodies were discovered in the 1980s and two were reported missing in 2005 but the remains of the other two were never found, police said. Detectives said they linked Franklin to the six additional killings after reviewing hundreds of old case files and seeking the public's help in identifying a collection of 180 photographs of women and girls that were found in his possession.<ref>{{cite web |last= Kandel |first= Jason |title= Police tie \"Grim Sleeper\" suspect to six more killings |publisher= Reuters |date= 3 November 2011 |url= https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/11/03/us-crime-grimsleeper-idUSTRE7A20L120111103 |accessdate= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last= Rubin |first= Joel |title= Police link 6 more slayings to Grim Sleeper suspect |work= Los Angeles Times |publisher= |date= 29 October 2011 |url= http://articles.latimes.com/2011/oct/29/local/la-me-grim-sleeper-20111029 |accessdate= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last= Olivia |first= Katrandjian |author2=Lauren Effron |author3=Lauren Sher |author4=Neal Karlinsky |title= Six More Deaths Linked to Grim Sleeper Serial Killer |work= abc NIGHTLINE |publisher= abc NEWS |date= 29 October 2011 |url= http://abcnews.go.com/US/deaths-linked-grim-sleeper-serial-killer/story?id=14842183#.TwMkn_KDtXU |accessdate= }}</ref>\n\nFranklin was charged with ten murders and one [[attempted murder]]. He was held without [[bail bond|bail]] until he received his [[death sentence]].<ref name=LATimes1>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/jul/16/local/la-me-0716-grim-sleeper-search-20100716|title=Police Collect Hundreds of Pieces of Evidence from Grim Sleeper Suspect's Home|work=Los Angeles Times|date=2010-07-16|accessdate=2010-07-23|first1=Andrew|last1=Blankstein|first2=Joel|last2=Rubin}}</ref> He is not charged in the death of an eleventh suspected victim, a black man, a crime for which DNA evidence was not found.<ref name=yahoonews1>{{cite news |url=https://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20100709/ap_on_re_us/us_grim_sleeper_killings_34#mwpphu-container|title=LA 'Grim Sleeper' Probe to Check Unsolved Killings|publisher=Yahoo! News|date=2010-07-09|accessdate=2010-07-23}}</ref> On May 5, 2016, after nearly three months of trial and a day and a half of jury deliberation, Franklin was convicted of ten counts of murder and one count of attempted murder.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://abc7.com/news/lonnie-franklin-jr-found-guilty-in-grim-sleeper-case/1325243/|title=Lonnie Franklin Jr. found guilty in 'Grim Sleeper' case|website=ABC7 Los Angeles|access-date=2016-05-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-grim-sleeper-verdict-20160504-story.html|title=Guilty verdicts in Grim Sleeper serial killer case|last=Times|first=Los Angeles|website=latimes.com|access-date=2016-05-05}}</ref> On June 6, 2016, a [[Los Angeles County]] jury sentenced Franklin to death.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-grim-sleeper-death-verdict-20160606-snap-story.html|title=Jurors vote for death sentence for 'Grim Sleeper' serial killer|first=James Queally, Marisa|last=Gerber|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Victims==\nThe known killings began in 1985 in South Los Angeles. The \"Grim Sleeper\" apparently took a 14-year hiatus after his last known crime in 1988 and the murders then resumed in 2002 (leading to the epithet by which he is known), but this history may be only an accident of the evidence collected. The last confirmed slaying was in January 2007.<ref name=abcnews1/> All of his victims were found outdoors, often in alleys a short distance from downtown Los Angeles.<ref name=foxnews>{{cite news |url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2010/07/07/arrest-la-grim-sleeper-killings/|title=Arrest Made in L.A. 'Grim Sleeper' Killings|publisher=FOX News|date=2010-07-07|accessdate=2010-07-23}}</ref>\n\nAll but one of his victims were black women. One of his suspected victims was a black man.<ref name=LATimes1/> Many of his victims were prostitutes.  One witness recalls that Franklin frequently brought prostitutes into his home. He shot all of his victims with a .25 caliber gun.<ref name=abcnews1/> Franklin took many photographs of nude women and kept the records in his garage.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20100708/ap_on_re_us/us_grim_sleeper_killings_23|title=Accused LA Serial Killer Said to Visit Prostitutes |publisher=Yahoo! News|date=2010-07-08|accessdate=2010-07-23}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\nFranklin's victims are as follows:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tiki-toki.com/timeline/entry/260246/Grim-Sleeper-Investigation-Timeline#vars!date=1985-11-02_13:12:56! |title='Grim Sleeper' Timeline |publisher=grimsleeper.wordpress.com |accessdate=2014-03-25}}</ref><ref name=GrimSleeperVictims>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-grim-sleeper-victims-snap-htmlstory.html|title=Grim Sleeper's victims were vulnerable, young and at times ignored|date=May 5, 2016|website=Los Angeles Times}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Number\n! Name\n! Sex\n! Age\n! Body found\n! Neighborhood\n|-\n| 1\n| {{sortname|Debra Ronette|Jackson|nolink=1}}\n| F\n| 29\n| {{dts|1985|August|10}}\n| [[Vermont-Slauson, Los Angeles]]\n|-\n| 2\n| {{sortname|Henrietta|Wright|nolink=1}}\n| F\n| 34\n| {{dts|1986|August|12}}\n| [[Hyde Park, Los Angeles]]\n|-\n| 3\n| {{sortname|Thomas Sylvester|Steele|nolink=1}} <sup>\u2021</sup>\n| M\n| 36\n| {{dts|1986|August|14}}\n| [[Harvard Park, Los Angeles]]\n|-\n| 4\n| {{sortname|Barbara Bethune|Ware|nolink=1}}\n| F\n| 23\n| {{dts|1987|January|10}}\n| [[Central-Alameda, Los Angeles]]\n|-\n| 5\n| {{sortname|Bernita Rochelle|Sparks|nolink=1}}\n| F\n| 26\n| {{dts|1987|April|15}}\n| [[Gramercy Park, Los Angeles]]\n|-\n| 6\n| {{sortname|Mary Katherine|Lowe|nolink=1}}\n| F\n| 26\n| {{dts|1987|November|1}}\n| [[Gramercy Park, Los Angeles]]\n|-\n| 7\n| {{sortname|Lachrica Denise|Jefferson|nolink=1}}\n| F\n| 22\n| {{dts|1988|January|30}}\n| [[Westmont, California|Westmont, Los Angeles County]]\n|-\n| 8\n| {{sortname|Alice Monique|Alexander|nolink=1}}\n| F\n| 18\n| {{dts|1988|September|11}}\n| [[Vermont Square, Los Angeles]]\n|-\n| 9\n| {{sortname|Enietra Margette|Washington|nolink=1}}<sup>\u2021\u2021</sup>\n| F\n| 30\n| Survived\n| [[Gramercy Park, Los Angeles]]\n|-\n| 10\n| {{sortname|Princess Cheyanne|Berthomieux|nolink=1}}\n| F\n| 15\n| {{dts|2002|March|19}}\n| [[Inglewood, California]]\n|-\n| 11\n| {{sortname|Valerie Louise|McCorvey|nolink=1}}\n| F\n| 35\n| {{dts|2003|July|11}}\n| [[Westmont, California|Westmont, Los Angeles County]]\n|-\n| 12\n| {{sortname|Janecia Lavette|Peters|nolink=1}}\n| F\n| 25\n| {{dts|2007|January|1}}\n| [[Gramercy Park, Los Angeles]]\n|}\n<sup>\u2021</sup> One of Franklin's suspected victims, although there is no DNA evidence to support the accusation.<ref name=yahoonews1/> Police said that the male victim, Thomas Steele, possibly was a friend of another victim or had discovered the killer's identity.<ref name=foxnews/><br/>\n<sup>\u2021\u2021</sup> Enietra \"Margette\" was told to use her middle name as her last name for her protection, but has since come forward as Enietra Margette Washington. Attacked on November 20, 1988, she is the only known survivor.<ref name=LAWeekly0/>\n\n==Trial==\nOn July 7, 2010, Lonnie David Franklin Jr., 57, was arrested. The Los Angeles County District Attorney's Office charged him with ten counts of murder, one count of attempted murder, and special circumstance allegations of multiple murders in the case.<ref name=CNN1>{{cite news |last= Simon |first=Mallory |title= Police Suspect in Los Angeles Grim Sleeper case to be arraigned |work= [[CNN.com]] |date= 2010-07-08 |url= http://www.cnn.com/2010/CRIME/07/08/grim.sleeper.case/index.html?hpt=T2 |accessdate= 2010-07-08}}</ref><ref name=MSNBC1>{{cite news |last= The Associated Press |title= Police make arrest in 'Grim Sleeper' killings |work= NBC News |date= 2010-07-07 |url= http://www.nbcnews.com/id/38133825 |accessdate= 2010-07-07}}</ref>\n\nAfter a lengthy pretrial [[Discovery (law)|discovery]]<ref name=CBS_LA1>[http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2013/12/02/grim-sleepers-defense-attorney-asks-to-photograph-nearly-900-pieces-of-evidence/ Grim Sleeper's Defense Attorney Asks To Photograph Nearly 900 Pieces Of Evidence], CBS Los Angeles (December 2, 2013)</ref> and several delays, the trial opened on February 16, 2016.<ref name=\"dailyherald.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyherald.com/article/20150206/news/302069980|title=Judge sets June trial date in 'Grim Sleeper' serial killings|first=BRIAN|last=MELLEY|date=6 February 2015|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=LATimes3>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-trial-delayed-in-grim-sleeper-serial-killings-case-20150522-story.html|title=Trial delayed in 'Grim Sleeper' serial killings case|date=May 22, 2015|website=Los Angeles Times}}</ref><ref name=CBS_LA2>[http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2015/08/17/judge-postpones-trial-date-in-grim-sleeper-killings/ Judge Postpones Trial Date In Grim Sleeper Killings], CBS Los Angeles (17 August 2015).</ref><ref name=LAWeekly2>[http://www.laweekly.com/news/grim-sleeper-trial-delayed-yet-again-as-antics-continue-5926244 Grim Sleeper Trial Delayed Yet Again as Antics Continue], LA Weekly (17 August 2015).</ref><ref name=LATimes4>[http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-grim-sleeper-trial-20150817-story.html Grim Sleeper serial killings: Repeatedly delayed trial is set for Oct. 14], Los Angeles Times (17 August 2015).</ref><ref name=LATimes2>[http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-grim-sleeper-serial-killings-case-delayed-20150918-story.html 'Grim Sleeper' serial killings trial delayed again], Los Angeles Times (18 September 2015).</ref><ref>[http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-grim-sleeper-serial-killer-trial-20160216-story.html Grim Sleeper serial killer trial begins, years after slayings terrorized South L.A.], Los Angeles Times (16 February 2016)</ref><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2016/feb/16/grim-sleeper-serial-killer-murder-trial-south-los-angeles-california 'Day of reckoning is here': Grim Sleeper murder trial begins in Los Angeles], The Guardian (17 February 2016)</ref> Closing arguments began May 2, 2016<ref>[http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2016/05/02/closing-arguments-grim-sleeper-trial/?e=o8Tn-Ny*OAG9Ww Closing Arguments Begin In 'Grim Sleeper' Trial], CBS Los Angeles (2 May 2016)</ref> and the jury began deliberating May 4, 2016.<ref>[http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2016/05/04/jury-begins-deliberating-case-of-accused-grim-sleeper-killer/ Jury Begins Deliberating Case Of Accused 'Grim Sleeper' Killer], CBS Los Angeles (4 May 2016).</ref> The jury convicted Franklin on all counts on May 5, 2016.<ref>[http://www.cnn.com/2016/05/05/us/grim-sleeper-trial-verdict/index.html Los Angeles jury convicts 'Grim Sleeper' of 10 murders] CNN (5 May 2016)</ref> On June 6, 2016, the jury rendered a verdict of death.<ref>[http://abc7.com/news/decision-reached-in-penalty-phase-for-grim-sleeper/1373724/ 'Grim Sleeper', convicted serial killer Lonnie Franklin Jr., sentenced to death] ABC7 Los Angeles (6 June 2016)</ref>\nOn August 10 the Superior Court sentenced Franklin on each count, naming the individual victims.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Death==\nOn March 28, 2020, Franklin was found unresponsive in his cell and was pronounced dead at 7:43 p.m.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/grim-sleeper-serial-killer-lonnie-franklin-jr-found-dead-prison-n1171686|title='Grim Sleeper' serial killer Lonnie Franklin Jr. found dead in prison cell|website=NBC News}}</ref> His cause of death is pending the results of an autopsy; however, there were no signs of trauma.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==Film and television==\n* In 2014, British filmmaker [[Nick Broomfield]] created a documentary film about Franklin, ''[[Tales of the Grim Sleeper]].''<ref>\"Overlooked by authorities in America, a British filmmaker tackles the Grim Sleeper\", ''Toronto Star'', 25 April 2014, WD5.</ref>\n* In 2014, [[Lifetime (TV network)|Lifetime]] premiered a movie, ''The Grim Sleeper'', based on the case. It was produced by [[Michael Jaffe]] Films Ltd. and stars [[Dreama Walker]], [[Macy Gray]], [[Ernie Hudson]], and [[Michael O'Neill (actor)|Micheal O\u2019Neill]].\n* The story was covered during season 1 of the [[Investigation Discovery]] show ''The Face of Evil'' in episode 4 titled, \"The Grim Sleeper\", which premiered on May 9, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Face of Evil|url=https://www.investigationdiscovery.com/tv-shows/the-face-of-evil//|date=May 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Biography|Film|Television}}\n* [[List of serial killers in the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Brittny Mejia, [http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-grim-sleeper-defense-backtracks-expert-witness-20151109-story.html Grim Sleeper: Defense Backtracks on Expert Witness,\"] Brittny Mejia, ''Los Angeles Times,'' November 9, 2015\n*Christine Pelisek, [http://www.laweekly.com/informer/2008/09/02/la-weekly-catches-grief-over-serial-killer-nickname LA Weekly Catches Grief Over Serial Killer Nickname], ''LA Weekly,'' September 2, 2008\n*Joel Rubin and Richard Winton, [http://articles.latimes.com/2008/aug/29/local/me-killer29 Police on the Hunt for Serial Killer] Los Angeles Times,'' August 29, 2008\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.lapdonline.org/grimsleeper Los Angeles Police Department \"Grim Sleeper\" page]{{mdashb}}features photographs of unidentified potential victims\n*[http://www.cnn.com/SPECIALS/2009/news/grim.sleeper/index.html CNN.com - Grim Sleeper] CNN Special Report; includes list of victims, connections, evidence, suspects, theories, and key persons involved\n*[https://mapsengine.google.com/map/edit?mid=z9nqTcv1k7Vs.kgaHeipIUEHE GoogleMaps locations] Google map of Grim Sleeper locations\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:1985 murders in the United States]]\n[[Category:2002 murders in the United States]]\n[[Category:20th-century American criminals]]\n[[Category:21st-century American criminals]]\n[[Category:African-American people]]\n[[Category:American male criminals]]\n[[Category:American criminals]]\n[[Category:American murderers of children]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of attempted murder]]\n[[Category:American prisoners sentenced to death]]\n[[Category:American serial killers]]\n[[Category:Crime in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Criminals from California]]\n[[Category:Crimes against sex workers in the United States]]\n[[Category:Crime in California]]\n[[Category:Criminals of Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Male serial killers]]\n[[Category:Murder in California]]\n[[Category:People convicted of murder by California]]\n[[Category:Prisoners sentenced to death by California]]\n[[Category:Sexual assaults in the United States]]\n[[Category:Violence against women in the United States]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of rape]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American serial killer (1952-2020)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox murderer\n|birth_name= Lonnie David Franklin Jr.\n|image= Lonnie David Franklin (Grim Sleeper).png\n|caption= LAPD mug shot 1998\n|birth_date= {{birth date|1952|08|30}}\n|birth_place= [[Los Angeles, California]], U.S.\n|death_date={{death date and age|2020|03|28|1952|08|30}}\n|death_place= [[San Quentin State Prison]]\n|alias= Grim Sleeper<br>Southside Slayer<br>25 Auto Killer<br>\n|sentence= [[Capital punishment in the United States|Death]]\n|victims= 10-25+ victims, 1 survivor (known)\n|country= United States\n|states= California\n|beginyear= 1985\n|endyear= 2007 (known murders)\n|apprehended= July 7, 2010\n|children= 2\n}}\n\n'''Lonnie David Franklin, Jr.''' (August 30, 1952 &ndash; March 28, 2020),<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2020-03-29/grim-sleeper-serial-killer-lonnie-franklin-dies-death-row-san-quentin|title='Grim Sleeper' serial killer Lonnie Franklin dies on death row at San Quentin|date=March 29, 2020|website=Los Angeles Times}}</ref> better known by the nickname '''Grim Sleeper''', was an American [[serial killer]] who was responsible for at least ten murders and one attempted murder in [[Los Angeles]], California.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/crime/grim-sleeper-serial-killer-lonnie-franklin-dead/|title='Grim Sleeper' Serial Killer Lonnie Franklin Dies in California Prison Cell|website=PEOPLE.com}}</ref> He was also convicted for [[rape]] and [[sexual violence]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/grim-sleeper-guilty-killings_us_572bb5e3e4b016f37895382f|title=Man Found Guilty For All 10 'Grim Sleeper' Killings Of Women|date=2016-05-05|website=The Huffington Post|access-date=2016-05-05}}</ref><ref name=LAWeekly0>Christine Pelisek, [http://www.laweekly.com/2008-08-28/news/grim-sleeper/. Grim Sleeper Returns: He's Murdering Angelenos, as Cops Hunt his DNA], ''LA Weekly'', August 28, 2008</ref><ref name=sky>[http://news.sky.com/story/631629/grim-sleeper-serial-killer-hunted Grim Sleeper Serial Killer Hunted ] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160610190831/http://news.sky.com/story/631629/grim-sleeper-serial-killer-hunted |date=2016-06-10 }}, SkyNews Report</ref> Franklin earned his nickname when he appeared to have taken a 14-year break from his crimes, from 1988 to 2002.<ref name=msn>{{cite web |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/38133825 |title=Arrest in 'Grim Sleeper' killings of ten women, man |publisher=NBC News |accessdate=2010-07-08}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2010, Franklin was arrested as a suspect, and, after many delays, his trial began in February 2016. On May 5, 2016, the jury convicted him of killing nine women and one teenage girl.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/05/05/us/grim-sleeper-trial-verdict/index.html|title=Jury convicts 'Grim Sleeper' of 10 murders|author=Scott Glover and Paul Vercammen|website=CNN|access-date=2016-05-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/trial-begins-alleged-grim-sleeper-serial-killer-lonnie/story?id=36974945|title=Trial Begins for Accused 'Grim Sleeper' Serial Killer|date=2016-02-17|publisher=ABC News|access-date=2016-05-05}}</ref> On June 6, 2016, the jury recommended the [[death penalty]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-grim-sleeper-death-verdict-20160606-snap-story.html|title=Jurors vote for death sentence for 'Grim Sleeper' serial killer|last=Times|first=Los Angeles|website=latimes.com|access-date=2016-06-06}}</ref> and on August 10, 2016, the Los Angeles Superior Court sentenced him to death for each of the ten victims named in the verdict.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-grim-sleeper-sentencing-20160810-snap-story.html|title=The 'Grim Sleeper' is sentenced to death for string of murders|last=Gerber|first=Marisa|last2=Queally|first2=James|date=10 August 2016|website=latimes.com|publisher=Los Angeles Times|access-date=2016-08-10}}</ref>  On March 28, 2020, he was found unresponsive in his cell at [[San Quentin State Prison]] and pronounced dead.\n\n==Personal life==\nLonnie Franklin Jr. was born on August 30, 1952. He grew up in [[South Central Los Angeles]], California.{{cn|date=December 2019}} He married and had two children.{{cn|date=December 2019}} He was given a [[general discharge]] from the [[United States Army]] on July 24, 1975, after having been released from prison for his conviction of gang-raping a 17-year-old girl in [[Stuttgart]], [[West Germany]].<ref name=\"people.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/crime/grim-sleeper-serial-killer-lonnie-franklin-once-gang-raped-a-german-teen/|title='Grim Sleeper' Serial Killer Lonnie Franklin Once Gang Raped a German Teen|website=PEOPLE.com}}</ref>\n\nFranklin and two other servicemen stationed in Stuttgart stopped to ask directions from the teen then offered her a ride home. When she accepted, they put a knife to her throat, drove her to a field and repeatedly raped her. She was able to feign interest in Franklin and asked for his phone number, by which police identified him.<ref name=\"people.com\"/>\n\nDuring the [[gang rape]] photographs were taken by one of the rapists \u2013 as was the case with the women Lonnie Franklin raped and murdered.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abc7.com/1356478/|title=Grim Sleeper jury to hear testimony from earliest known victim|date=May 26, 2016|website=ABC7 Los Angeles}}</ref>\n\nIn 1989, he was also convicted of two charges of theft, one charge of misdemeanor assault, and one charge of [[Battery (crime)|battery]]. He served time for one of the theft charges.<ref name=abcnews1>{{cite news |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Nightline/familys-dna-led-police-grim-sleeper-serial-killer/story?id=11116381&page=2|title=New Technique of Using Family's DNA Led Police to 'Grim Sleeper' Suspect|publisher=ABC News|date=2010-07-08|accessdate=2010-07-23}}</ref>\n\n==Investigation==\nIn the 1980s, the [[Los Angeles Police Department|LAPD]] marked the deaths of several women in [[South Los Angeles, California|South Los Angeles]] with the identification \u201cNHI\u201d, meaning \"no humans involved\",{{citation needed|date=November 2019}} which was used for cases involving chronic [[drug user]]s and [[prostitution in the United States|prostitutes]]. Margaret Prescod formed the \"Black Women Count\" movement with community members to pressure the LAPD into acknowledging the deaths as serial killings and forming a task force in response. The coalition launched a media campaign and set a monetary reward aiming to capture the killer. The joint LAPD-[[Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department]] investigation determined that the crimes were committed by a single person labeled the \"Southside Slayer\". Their results were announced to the public on September 23, 1985.<ref name=SSS/>\n\nAccording to investigators, evidence was found suggesting that several serial killers were murdering women in South Los Angeles. [[Louis Craine]] committed at least two of the \"Southside Slayer\" murders, and [[Michael Hughes (serial killer)|Michael Hughes]], [[Daniel Lee Siebert]], [[Chester Turner]], and [[Ivan Hill]] committed at least one each.<ref>{{cite web |title= Map: Serial Killers in South L.A. |work= Los Angeles Times |date= 3 August 2010 |url= http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-serialkillersmap-0804-i,0,515310.htmlstory |accessdate= }}</ref> A separate series of killings commenced with the murder of Debra Jackson and a different ''[[modus operandi]]'' involving a firearm.<ref name=SSS>{{cite web |last= Jones |first= Jack |title= Man Sought in Slayings of 10 L.A.-Area Prostitutes |work= Los Angeles Times |publisher= |date= 24 September 1985 |url= http://articles.latimes.com/1985-09-24/news/mn-18536_1 |accessdate= }}</ref> These became known, misleadingly, as the \"Strawberry Murders.\" Sheriff's Detective Rickey Ross was wrongfully arrested due to a ballistics error. Two decades later, the perpetrator of these crimes was dubbed the \"Grim Sleeper\" due to the long period of apparent inactivity between murders.<ref>{{cite web |author=Jill Stewart |url=http://www.laweekly.com/2010-07-15/news/missing-the-grim-sleeper-by-a-hair/1 |title=Missing the Grim Sleeper by a Hair|work=LA Weekly |date=2010-07-15 |accessdate=2010-12-18}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2007, the slaying of Janecia Peters, 25, was linked through [[DNA]] analysis to at least eleven unsolved murders in Los Angeles, the first of which occurred in 1985. That same year, in secrecy, the LAPD formed the \"800 Task Force,\" composed of six detectives and overseen by the Robbery-Homicide Unit. After a four-month investigation, ''[[LA Weekly]]'' [[investigative journalism|investigative reporter]] Christine Pelisek broke the news of the task force's existence, the link between Peters' killing and the earlier murders, and the silence of [[Mayor of Los Angeles|Mayor]] [[Antonio Villaraigosa]] and Police Chief [[William J. Bratton]] regarding the killer's existence. Villaraigosa and Bratton neither issued a press release nor warned the community. In some cases, ''LA Weekly'' was the first to inform the families that their daughters had long been confirmed as victims of a serial killer.<ref name=LAWeekly0/>\n\nIn early September 2008, Los Angeles officials announced that they were offering a $500,000 reward to help catch the killer.<ref name=sky/> On November 1, the case was featured on the [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] program ''[[America's Most Wanted]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.amw.com/fugitives/brief.cfm?id=60381/ |title=Most Wanted fugitives website (defunct) |date= |work=[[America's Most Wanted]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022040939/http://www.amw.com/ |archivedate=2012-10-22 |accessdate=2015-02-20}}{{full citation needed|date=July 2010}}</ref> On February 25, 2009, Bratton addressed the press for the first time regarding the case, at which time the police formally gave the killer the \"Grim Sleeper\" nickname chosen by ''LA Weekly''. Bratton also released a [[9-1-1]] call from the 1980s in which a man reported seeing a body being dumped by Franklin, giving a detailed description and license plate number of a van connected with the now-closed Cosmopolitan Church.<ref>{{cite web |last=Pelisek |first=Christine |url=http://blogs.laweekly.com/ladaily/1tape-may-hold-clue-to-identif/ |title=Tape May Hold Clue to Identifying Grim Sleeper Serial Killer \u2013 Los Angeles News \u2013 The Informer |publisher=Blogs.laweekly.com |date=2009-02-25 |accessdate=2010-07-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090803080447/http://blogs.laweekly.com/ladaily/1tape-may-hold-clue-to-identif/ |archive-date=2009-08-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2009, Pelisek conducted an extensive interview with Enietra Washington, the sole survivor of Franklin's attacks.<ref>{{cite web |author=Christine Pelisek |url=http://www.laweekly.com/2008-08-28/news/grim-sleeper/4 |title=Grim Sleeper Returns: He's Murdering Angelenos, as Cops Hunt his DNA|work=LA Weekly |date=2008-08-28 |accessdate=2010-07-08}}</ref><ref name=LAWeekly1>{{cite web |author=Christine Pelisek |url=http://www.laweekly.com/2009-03-12/news/grim-sleeper-39-s-sole-survivor/2 |title=Grim Sleeper's Sole Survivor|work=LA Weekly |date=2009-03-12 |accessdate=2010-07-08}}</ref> Washington described him as \"a black man in his early 30s [\u2060\u200a\u2060.\u2060\u200a\u2060.\u2060\u200a\u2060.\u2060\u200a\u2060] He looked neat. Tidy. Kind of geeky. He wore a black polo shirt tucked into khaki trousers.\" She also described the interior and exterior of his vehicle.<ref name=survive>{{cite web |author=Christine Pelisek |url=http://www.laweekly.com/2009-03-12/news/grim-sleeper-39-s-sole-survivor/ |title=Grim Sleeper's Sole Survivor|work=LA Weekly |date=2009-03-12 |accessdate=2010-07-08}}</ref>\n\n==Arrest==\nOn July 7, 2010, the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' reported that an arrest had been made. Los Angeles County District Attorney Steve Cooley identified the suspect as 57-year-old Lonnie David Franklin Jr., a mechanic who worked between 1981 and 1988 for the City of Los Angeles in the sanitation department and briefly for the LAPD.<ref name=msn/> Franklin was identified for arrest, at least in part, on [[DNA profiling#DNA evidence as evidence in criminal trials|familial DNA analysis]].<ref name=latimesblog>{{cite news |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2010/07/lapd-make-arrest-in-grim-sleeper-serial-killings.html |title=LAPD make arrest in Grim Sleeper serial killings |publisher=Latimesblogs.latimes.com |date= 2010-07-07|accessdate=2010-07-08}}</ref>\n\nPolice had found no exact match between DNA found at the crime scenes and any of the profiles in California's DNA profile database, so they searched the database for stored profiles that demonstrated sufficient similarity to allow police to infer a familial relationship. They found similar DNA belonging to Franklin's son, Christopher, who had been convicted of a [[felony]] weapons charge. According to Cooley, detectives then used a piece of discarded pizza with Franklin's DNA to make the link.<ref name=yahoonews1/>\n\nOne undercover police officer pretended to be a waiter at a restaurant where Franklin ate, collecting dishes, silverware, glasses, and pizza crusts to obtain DNA.<ref name=yahoonews1/> The identification was used to arrest Franklin after his DNA was obtained and deemed a match.<ref name=CNN1/> Saliva found on the victims established a DNA match linking Franklin to the deaths.<ref name=abcnews1/>\n\nLaw enforcement missed an opportunity to catch Franklin because his DNA was not previously collected. In 2003, Franklin was convicted of a felony and was serving three years of supervised [[probation]]. In 2004, voters passed [[California Proposition 69 (2004)|Proposition 69]], which requires that DNA must be collected from all felons and everyone arrested on some specified charges. It also requires the expansion of the DNA database. Authorities collected and sorted through thousands of DNA samples. While he was on probation, Franklin's DNA was supposed to be entered in the system but was not as probation officers did not collect samples from people who were on unsupervised probation between November 2004 and August 2005. The probation department did not have the resources to collect samples until August 2005.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/jul/15/local/la-me-grim-sleeper-dna-20100715|title=Authorities Missed A Chance to Catch Grim Sleeper Suspect|work=Los Angeles Times|date=2010-07-15|accessdate=2010-07-23|first=Jack|last=Leonard}}</ref>\n\nOn December 16, 2010, the LAPD released 180 photos of women, found in Franklin's home after unsuccessful attempts to identify the individuals, possibly additional victims. \"These people are not suspects, we don't even know if they are victims, but we do know this: Lonnie Franklin's reign of terror in the city of Los Angeles, which spanned well over two decades, culminating with almost a dozen murder victims, certainly needs to be investigated further,\" said Police Chief [[Charlie Beck]].<ref name=reuters1/>\n\nIn all, investigators found over 1,000 photos and several hundred hours of video in his home.<ref name=reuters1>{{cite news |last=Whitcomb |first=Dan |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSTRE6BF6EU20101216 |title=L.A. police release photos of possible Grim Sleeper victims |publisher=Reuters |date= 2010-12-16|accessdate=2010-12-18}}</ref> The images show mainly black women of a wide age range, from teenagers to middle-aged and older, often nude. Police believe Franklin took many of the pictures, which show both conscious and unconscious individuals, dating back 30 years.<ref name=reuters1/> The photos were released to the public in an effort to identify the women.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hayes |first=Kevin |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-504083_162-20026038-504083.html |title=\"Grim Sleeper\" Photos: LAPD Deluged with Calls - Crimesider |publisher=CBS News |accessdate=2010-12-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://abcnews.go.com/TheLaw/grim-sleeper-serial-killer-victim-photos-released-los/story?id=12424559 |title=Five Women Tentatively Identified in 'Grim Sleeper' Cas - ABC News |publisher=Abcnews.go.com |accessdate=2010-12-18}}</ref>\n\nOn November 3, 2011, [[Reuters]] reported that the police were considering Franklin as a suspect in six more slayings of additional female victims. The police were investigating two of the six as potential victims killed during a 14-year lapse between an initial spate of Grim Sleeper murders that ended in 1988 and several more that began in 2002. Of the remaining four victims, two bodies were discovered in the 1980s and two were reported missing in 2005 but the remains of the other two were never found, police said. Detectives said they linked Franklin to the six additional killings after reviewing hundreds of old case files and seeking the public's help in identifying a collection of 180 photographs of women and girls that were found in his possession.<ref>{{cite web |last= Kandel |first= Jason |title= Police tie \"Grim Sleeper\" suspect to six more killings |publisher= Reuters |date= 3 November 2011 |url= https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/11/03/us-crime-grimsleeper-idUSTRE7A20L120111103 |accessdate= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last= Rubin |first= Joel |title= Police link 6 more slayings to Grim Sleeper suspect |work= Los Angeles Times |publisher= |date= 29 October 2011 |url= http://articles.latimes.com/2011/oct/29/local/la-me-grim-sleeper-20111029 |accessdate= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last= Olivia |first= Katrandjian |author2=Lauren Effron |author3=Lauren Sher |author4=Neal Karlinsky |title= Six More Deaths Linked to Grim Sleeper Serial Killer |work= abc NIGHTLINE |publisher= abc NEWS |date= 29 October 2011 |url= http://abcnews.go.com/US/deaths-linked-grim-sleeper-serial-killer/story?id=14842183#.TwMkn_KDtXU |accessdate= }}</ref>\n\nFranklin was charged with ten murders and one [[attempted murder]]. He was held without [[bail bond|bail]] until he received his [[death sentence]].<ref name=LATimes1>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/jul/16/local/la-me-0716-grim-sleeper-search-20100716|title=Police Collect Hundreds of Pieces of Evidence from Grim Sleeper Suspect's Home|work=Los Angeles Times|date=2010-07-16|accessdate=2010-07-23|first1=Andrew|last1=Blankstein|first2=Joel|last2=Rubin}}</ref> He is not charged in the death of an eleventh suspected victim, a black man, a crime for which DNA evidence was not found.<ref name=yahoonews1>{{cite news |url=https://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20100709/ap_on_re_us/us_grim_sleeper_killings_34#mwpphu-container|title=LA 'Grim Sleeper' Probe to Check Unsolved Killings|publisher=Yahoo! News|date=2010-07-09|accessdate=2010-07-23}}</ref> On May 5, 2016, after nearly three months of trial and a day and a half of jury deliberation, Franklin was convicted of ten counts of murder and one count of attempted murder.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://abc7.com/news/lonnie-franklin-jr-found-guilty-in-grim-sleeper-case/1325243/|title=Lonnie Franklin Jr. found guilty in 'Grim Sleeper' case|website=ABC7 Los Angeles|access-date=2016-05-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-grim-sleeper-verdict-20160504-story.html|title=Guilty verdicts in Grim Sleeper serial killer case|last=Times|first=Los Angeles|website=latimes.com|access-date=2016-05-05}}</ref> On June 6, 2016, a [[Los Angeles County]] jury sentenced Franklin to death.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-grim-sleeper-death-verdict-20160606-snap-story.html|title=Jurors vote for death sentence for 'Grim Sleeper' serial killer|first=James Queally, Marisa|last=Gerber|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Victims==\nThe known killings began in 1985 in South Los Angeles. The \"Grim Sleeper\" apparently took a 14-year hiatus after his last known crime in 1988 and the murders then resumed in 2002 (leading to the epithet by which he is known), but this history may be only an accident of the evidence collected. The last confirmed slaying was in January 2007.<ref name=abcnews1/> All of his victims were found outdoors, often in alleys a short distance from downtown Los Angeles.<ref name=foxnews>{{cite news |url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2010/07/07/arrest-la-grim-sleeper-killings/|title=Arrest Made in L.A. 'Grim Sleeper' Killings|publisher=FOX News|date=2010-07-07|accessdate=2010-07-23}}</ref>\n\nAll but one of his victims were black women. One of his suspected victims was a black man.<ref name=LATimes1/> Many of his victims were prostitutes.  One witness recalls that Franklin frequently brought prostitutes into his home. He shot all of his victims with a .25 caliber gun.<ref name=abcnews1/> Franklin took many photographs of nude women and kept the records in his garage.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20100708/ap_on_re_us/us_grim_sleeper_killings_23|title=Accused LA Serial Killer Said to Visit Prostitutes |publisher=Yahoo! News|date=2010-07-08|accessdate=2010-07-23}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\nFranklin's victims are as follows:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tiki-toki.com/timeline/entry/260246/Grim-Sleeper-Investigation-Timeline#vars!date=1985-11-02_13:12:56! |title='Grim Sleeper' Timeline |publisher=grimsleeper.wordpress.com |accessdate=2014-03-25}}</ref><ref name=GrimSleeperVictims>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-grim-sleeper-victims-snap-htmlstory.html|title=Grim Sleeper's victims were vulnerable, young and at times ignored|date=May 5, 2016|website=Los Angeles Times}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Number\n! Name\n! Sex\n! Age\n! Body found\n! Neighborhood\n|-\n| 1\n| {{sortname|Debra Ronette|Jackson|nolink=1}}\n| F\n| 29\n| {{dts|1985|August|10}}\n| [[Vermont-Slauson, Los Angeles]]\n|-\n| 2\n| {{sortname|Henrietta|Wright|nolink=1}}\n| F\n| 34\n| {{dts|1986|August|12}}\n| [[Hyde Park, Los Angeles]]\n|-\n| 3\n| {{sortname|Thomas Sylvester|Steele|nolink=1}} <sup>\u2021</sup>\n| M\n| 36\n| {{dts|1986|August|14}}\n| [[Harvard Park, Los Angeles]]\n|-\n| 4\n| {{sortname|Barbara Bethune|Ware|nolink=1}}\n| F\n| 23\n| {{dts|1987|January|10}}\n| [[Central-Alameda, Los Angeles]]\n|-\n| 5\n| {{sortname|Bernita Rochelle|Sparks|nolink=1}}\n| F\n| 26\n| {{dts|1987|April|15}}\n| [[Gramercy Park, Los Angeles]]\n|-\n| 6\n| {{sortname|Mary Katherine|Lowe|nolink=1}}\n| F\n| 26\n| {{dts|1987|November|1}}\n| [[Gramercy Park, Los Angeles]]\n|-\n| 7\n| {{sortname|Lachrica Denise|Jefferson|nolink=1}}\n| F\n| 22\n| {{dts|1988|January|30}}\n| [[Westmont, California|Westmont, Los Angeles County]]\n|-\n| 8\n| {{sortname|Alice Monique|Alexander|nolink=1}}\n| F\n| 18\n| {{dts|1988|September|11}}\n| [[Vermont Square, Los Angeles]]\n|-\n| 9\n| {{sortname|Enietra Margette|Washington|nolink=1}}<sup>\u2021\u2021</sup>\n| F\n| 30\n| Survived\n| [[Gramercy Park, Los Angeles]]\n|-\n| 10\n| {{sortname|Princess Cheyanne|Berthomieux|nolink=1}}\n| F\n| 15\n| {{dts|2002|March|19}}\n| [[Inglewood, California]]\n|-\n| 11\n| {{sortname|Valerie Louise|McCorvey|nolink=1}}\n| F\n| 35\n| {{dts|2003|July|11}}\n| [[Westmont, California|Westmont, Los Angeles County]]\n|-\n| 12\n| {{sortname|Janecia Lavette|Peters|nolink=1}}\n| F\n| 25\n| {{dts|2007|January|1}}\n| [[Gramercy Park, Los Angeles]]\n|}\n<sup>\u2021</sup> One of Franklin's suspected victims, although there is no DNA evidence to support the accusation.<ref name=yahoonews1/> Police said that the male victim, Thomas Steele, possibly was a friend of another victim or had discovered the killer's identity.<ref name=foxnews/><br/>\n<sup>\u2021\u2021</sup> Enietra \"Margette\" was told to use her middle name as her last name for her protection, but has since come forward as Enietra Margette Washington. Attacked on November 20, 1988, she is the only known survivor.<ref name=LAWeekly0/>\n\n==Trial==\nOn July 7, 2010, Lonnie David Franklin Jr., 57, was arrested. The Los Angeles County District Attorney's Office charged him with ten counts of murder, one count of attempted murder, and special circumstance allegations of multiple murders in the case.<ref name=CNN1>{{cite news |last= Simon |first=Mallory |title= Police Suspect in Los Angeles Grim Sleeper case to be arraigned |work= [[CNN.com]] |date= 2010-07-08 |url= http://www.cnn.com/2010/CRIME/07/08/grim.sleeper.case/index.html?hpt=T2 |accessdate= 2010-07-08}}</ref><ref name=MSNBC1>{{cite news |last= The Associated Press |title= Police make arrest in 'Grim Sleeper' killings |work= NBC News |date= 2010-07-07 |url= http://www.nbcnews.com/id/38133825 |accessdate= 2010-07-07}}</ref>\n\nAfter a lengthy pretrial [[Discovery (law)|discovery]]<ref name=CBS_LA1>[http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2013/12/02/grim-sleepers-defense-attorney-asks-to-photograph-nearly-900-pieces-of-evidence/ Grim Sleeper's Defense Attorney Asks To Photograph Nearly 900 Pieces Of Evidence], CBS Los Angeles (December 2, 2013)</ref> and several delays, the trial opened on February 16, 2016.<ref name=\"dailyherald.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyherald.com/article/20150206/news/302069980|title=Judge sets June trial date in 'Grim Sleeper' serial killings|first=BRIAN|last=MELLEY|date=6 February 2015|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=LATimes3>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-trial-delayed-in-grim-sleeper-serial-killings-case-20150522-story.html|title=Trial delayed in 'Grim Sleeper' serial killings case|date=May 22, 2015|website=Los Angeles Times}}</ref><ref name=CBS_LA2>[http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2015/08/17/judge-postpones-trial-date-in-grim-sleeper-killings/ Judge Postpones Trial Date In Grim Sleeper Killings], CBS Los Angeles (17 August 2015).</ref><ref name=LAWeekly2>[http://www.laweekly.com/news/grim-sleeper-trial-delayed-yet-again-as-antics-continue-5926244 Grim Sleeper Trial Delayed Yet Again as Antics Continue], LA Weekly (17 August 2015).</ref><ref name=LATimes4>[http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-grim-sleeper-trial-20150817-story.html Grim Sleeper serial killings: Repeatedly delayed trial is set for Oct. 14], Los Angeles Times (17 August 2015).</ref><ref name=LATimes2>[http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-grim-sleeper-serial-killings-case-delayed-20150918-story.html 'Grim Sleeper' serial killings trial delayed again], Los Angeles Times (18 September 2015).</ref><ref>[http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-grim-sleeper-serial-killer-trial-20160216-story.html Grim Sleeper serial killer trial begins, years after slayings terrorized South L.A.], Los Angeles Times (16 February 2016)</ref><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2016/feb/16/grim-sleeper-serial-killer-murder-trial-south-los-angeles-california 'Day of reckoning is here': Grim Sleeper murder trial begins in Los Angeles], The Guardian (17 February 2016)</ref> Closing arguments began May 2, 2016<ref>[http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2016/05/02/closing-arguments-grim-sleeper-trial/?e=o8Tn-Ny*OAG9Ww Closing Arguments Begin In 'Grim Sleeper' Trial], CBS Los Angeles (2 May 2016)</ref> and the jury began deliberating May 4, 2016.<ref>[http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2016/05/04/jury-begins-deliberating-case-of-accused-grim-sleeper-killer/ Jury Begins Deliberating Case Of Accused 'Grim Sleeper' Killer], CBS Los Angeles (4 May 2016).</ref> The jury convicted Franklin on all counts on May 5, 2016.<ref>[http://www.cnn.com/2016/05/05/us/grim-sleeper-trial-verdict/index.html Los Angeles jury convicts 'Grim Sleeper' of 10 murders] CNN (5 May 2016)</ref> On June 6, 2016, the jury rendered a verdict of death.<ref>[http://abc7.com/news/decision-reached-in-penalty-phase-for-grim-sleeper/1373724/ 'Grim Sleeper', convicted serial killer Lonnie Franklin Jr., sentenced to death] ABC7 Los Angeles (6 June 2016)</ref>\nOn August 10 the Superior Court sentenced Franklin on each count, naming the individual victims.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Death==\nOn March 28, 2020, Franklin was found unresponsive in his cell and was pronounced dead at 7:43 p.m.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/grim-sleeper-serial-killer-lonnie-franklin-jr-found-dead-prison-n1171686|title='Grim Sleeper' serial killer Lonnie Franklin Jr. found dead in prison cell|website=NBC News}}</ref> His cause of death is pending the results of an autopsy; however, there were no signs of trauma.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==Film and television==\n* In 2014, British filmmaker [[Nick Broomfield]] created a documentary film about Franklin, ''[[Tales of the Grim Sleeper]].''<ref>\"Overlooked by authorities in America, a British filmmaker tackles the Grim Sleeper\", ''Toronto Star'', 25 April 2014, WD5.</ref>\n* In 2014, [[Lifetime (TV network)|Lifetime]] premiered a movie, ''The Grim Sleeper'', based on the case. It was produced by [[Michael Jaffe]] Films Ltd. and stars [[Dreama Walker]], [[Macy Gray]], [[Ernie Hudson]], and [[Michael O'Neill (actor)|Micheal O\u2019Neill]].\n* The story was covered during season 1 of the [[Investigation Discovery]] show ''The Face of Evil'' in episode 4 titled, \"The Grim Sleeper\", which premiered on May 9, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Face of Evil|url=https://www.investigationdiscovery.com/tv-shows/the-face-of-evil//|date=May 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Biography|Film|Television}}\n* [[List of serial killers in the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Brittny Mejia, [http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-grim-sleeper-defense-backtracks-expert-witness-20151109-story.html Grim Sleeper: Defense Backtracks on Expert Witness,\"] Brittny Mejia, ''Los Angeles Times,'' November 9, 2015\n*Christine Pelisek, [http://www.laweekly.com/informer/2008/09/02/la-weekly-catches-grief-over-serial-killer-nickname LA Weekly Catches Grief Over Serial Killer Nickname], ''LA Weekly,'' September 2, 2008\n*Joel Rubin and Richard Winton, [http://articles.latimes.com/2008/aug/29/local/me-killer29 Police on the Hunt for Serial Killer] Los Angeles Times,'' August 29, 2008\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.lapdonline.org/grimsleeper Los Angeles Police Department \"Grim Sleeper\" page]{{mdashb}}features photographs of unidentified potential victims\n*[http://www.cnn.com/SPECIALS/2009/news/grim.sleeper/index.html CNN.com - Grim Sleeper] CNN Special Report; includes list of victims, connections, evidence, suspects, theories, and key persons involved\n*[https://mapsengine.google.com/map/edit?mid=z9nqTcv1k7Vs.kgaHeipIUEHE GoogleMaps locations] Google map of Grim Sleeper locations\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:1985 murders in the United States]]\n[[Category:2002 murders in the United States]]\n[[Category:20th-century American criminals]]\n[[Category:21st-century American criminals]]\n[[Category:African-American people]]\n[[Category:American male criminals]]\n[[Category:American criminals]]\n[[Category:American murderers of children]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of attempted murder]]\n[[Category:American prisoners sentenced to death]]\n[[Category:American serial killers]]\n[[Category:Crime in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Criminals from California]]\n[[Category:Crimes against sex workers in the United States]]\n[[Category:Crime in California]]\n[[Category:Criminals of Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Male serial killers]]\n[[Category:Murder in California]]\n[[Category:People convicted of murder by California]]\n[[Category:Prisoners sentenced to death by California]]\n[[Category:Sexual assaults in the United States]]\n[[Category:Violence against women in the United States]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of rape]]\n", "name_user": "Srich32977", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grim_Sleeper"}
